### [Ambassador of the United States to Costa Rica](/Ambassador_of_the_United_States_to_Costa_Rica)

One might wonder why a comprehensive record of diplomatic postings to a nation like [Costa Rica](/Costa_Rica) is necessary. Yet, here we are. This document meticulously chronicles the individuals dispatched by the [United States](/United_States) to serve as their chief representatives in [Costa Rica](/Costa_Rica), a role that has evolved from a relatively minor diplomatic post to one of significant regional importance. From the earliest envoys, often juggling multiple Central American assignments, to the modern [Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary](/Ambassador), each entry marks a small, often unremarkable, chapter in the ongoing, occasionally strained, relationship between the two nations.

The position itself, currently held by Jennifer Savage in an interim capacity as [Chargé d'affaires](/Charg%C3%A9_d%27Affaires) (or at least, she will be, as of August 5, 2025, according to the records, which is a surprisingly specific prediction for such a fluid role), is a direct appointment by the sitting [president of the United States](/President_of_the_United_States). This nomination, a testament to the executive's prerogative, then faces the scrutiny of the [United States Senate](/United_States_Senate) for [advice and consent](/Advice_and_consent)—a process that, one can only imagine, is brimming with profound geopolitical insights and absolutely no political maneuvering. The inaugural holder of this distinction was [Solon Borland](/Solon_Borland), who began his tenure as an [Envoy Extraordinary and Minister Plenipotentiary](/Envoy_Extraordinary_and_Minister_Plenipotentiary), setting a precedent for a succession of figures whose primary directive was to represent U.S. interests, however those were defined at the time. Further details, for those truly compelled, can be found on the U.S. Embassy in San Jose's official website.

